            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this inheritance tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator gives a high-level estimate of inheritance tax
                in two different systems: the
                <strong>United Kingdom</strong> (estate-based tax) and
                <strong>Italy</strong> (per-beneficiary tax). It is deliberately
                simplified so that you can quickly explore “what if” scenarios.
              </p>

              <h3>UK inheritance tax – simplified model</h3>
              <p>
                In the UK, inheritance tax (IHT) is normally charged on the
                value of the estate on death above certain tax-free thresholds.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Basic steps (UK):</p>
                <ol class="list-decimal ml-4">
                  <li>Net estate = total estate − debts and funeral costs.</li>
                  <li>
                    Subtract amounts left to a UK-domiciled spouse/civil partner
                    and to qualifying charities (usually exempt).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Apply the <strong>nil-rate band (NRB)</strong> and any
                    <strong>residence nil-rate band (RNRB)</strong>.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    If applicable, add a <strong>transferable NRB</strong> from
                    a late spouse (up to 100%).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Taxable estate = remaining amount after all allowances.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Inheritance tax = taxable estate × rate (typically 40%, or
                    36% if the charity condition is met).
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </div>

              <p>
                The calculator lets you override the NRB, RNRB and rates so you
                can adapt to different tax years or special situations. It does
                <strong>not</strong> model every relief (e.g. business or
                agricultural property relief, taper relief on gifts,
                non-domiciled rules).
              </p>

              <h3>Italian inheritance tax – simplified model</h3>
              <p>
                In Italy, inheritance tax is calculated
                <strong>per beneficiary</strong>. Each heir has their own
                allowance and rate depending on their relationship to the
                deceased.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Basic steps (Italy):</p>
                <ol class="list-decimal ml-4">
                  <li>
                    For each beneficiary, determine their share of the estate.
                  </li>
                  <li>Apply the tax-free allowance for that relationship.</li>
                  <li>Taxable amount = max(0, share − allowance).</li>
                  <li>
                    Inheritance tax for that person = taxable amount × rate for
                    that relationship.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Total inheritance tax = sum of tax for all beneficiaries.
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </div>

              <p>
                Typical Italian rules (which you can override in the table):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Spouse and children</strong>: €1,000,000 allowance
                  each, 4% on the excess.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Brothers and sisters</strong>: €100,000 allowance
                  each, 6% on the excess.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Other relatives up to 4th degree, in-laws up to 3rd
                    degree</strong
                  >: 6% with no allowance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other beneficiaries</strong> (unrelated persons): 8%
                  with no allowance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator pre-fills these values when you choose a
                relationship, but you can edit the allowance and rate if you
                need to reflect special cases or future changes.
              </p>

              <h2>Key concepts and formulas</h2>

              <h3>1. Net estate</h3>
              <p>
                For both systems, the starting point is the
                <strong>net estate</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Net estate = Gross estate value − Debts − Funeral and
                  administration costs
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Taxable amount</h3>
              <p>
                Once exemptions and allowances are applied, the taxable amount
                is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Taxable amount = max(0, Net estate − Exempt transfers −
                  Allowances)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Inheritance tax</h3>
              <p>The basic tax formula is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Inheritance tax = Taxable amount × Tax rate</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In the UK, the tax rate can be reduced from 40% to 36% if at
                least 10% of the “baseline amount” is left to charity. This
                calculator approximates that test by comparing the charity
                amount to the net estate after allowances.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and professional advice</h2>
              <p>
                Inheritance tax law is complex and changes over time. This
                calculator <strong>does not</strong> cover:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  All possible reliefs (business property relief, agricultural
                  relief, heritage assets, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Detailed treatment of lifetime gifts, trusts, or foreign
                  assets.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Local surcharges, regional rules, or treaty interactions for
                  cross-border estates.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the results as a <strong>rough guide only</strong>. For real
                cases, especially cross-border estates or large amounts, speak
                to a qualified tax adviser or private client lawyer in the
                relevant country.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions about inheritance tax</h2>

              <h3>What is inheritance tax?</h3>
              <p>
                Inheritance tax is a tax on the transfer of wealth when someone
                dies (and in some systems, on certain lifetime gifts). Some
                countries tax the <strong>estate</strong> as a whole (like the
                UK), while others tax what each
                <strong>beneficiary</strong> receives (like Italy).
              </p>

              <h3>Who pays inheritance tax in the UK?</h3>
              <p>
                In the UK, inheritance tax is usually paid from the estate by
                the executor or personal representative before assets are
                distributed. Beneficiaries normally do not pay IHT themselves,
                although they may pay other taxes later (for example, capital
                gains tax if they sell inherited assets at a profit).
              </p>

              <h3>Who pays inheritance tax in Italy?</h3>
              <p>
                In Italy, the tax is assessed on each beneficiary based on their
                share and relationship to the deceased. The heir or legatee is
                generally responsible for the tax, but in practice the
                calculation and payment are often handled during the succession
                process with the assistance of a notary or tax professional.
              </p>

              <h3>Are gifts subject to inheritance tax?</h3>
              <p>
                In the UK, most gifts made within 7 years before death are
                potentially chargeable, although there are important exemptions
                (such as small gifts, normal expenditure out of income, and
                annual allowances) and taper relief for gifts made more than 3
                years before death.
              </p>
              <p>
                In Italy, lifetime gifts (donazioni) are generally subject to
                gift tax at the same rates and allowances as inheritance tax,
                and may be taken into account when calculating tax on the
                estate.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator legally binding?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is an educational tool. It uses simplified
                assumptions and may not reflect the latest law, local
                variations, or your specific circumstances. Always check
                official guidance (for example, from HMRC in the UK or the
                Italian tax authorities) and consult a qualified adviser before
                making financial or estate-planning decisions.
              </p>
            </section>
